          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \tau )]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topological space</fr:link> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \subseteq  X]]></fr:tex>. A point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> is a <html:strong>limit point</html:strong> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> if every <fr:link href="/gtop-0005/" title="Open Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0005/" display-uri="gtop-0005" type="local">open set</fr:link> containing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> also contains a point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> other than <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> itself.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
In a <fr:link href="/gtop-0003/" title="Metric Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0003/" display-uri="gtop-0003" type="local">metric space</fr:link>, this is equivalent to: there exists a sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\left \{ x_n \right \} \subseteq  S \setminus  \left \{ x \right \}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
